 <!-- Items in scope -->
 <inscope>
   <li>the existence of a class or set;</li>
   <li>

the distinction between a class or set that is defined by abstract criteria, and a class or set that is defined by enumerating its members;</li>


<li>a classification relationship between a class or set and a member;</li>

<li>a complete enumeration of the members for a class or set;</li>

<li>the following set theory relationships:
<ul>
<li>complement;</li>
<li>equivalence;</li>
<li>intersection;</li>
<li>power set;</li>
<li>proper subset;</li>
<li>subset;</li>
<li>union.</li>
</ul>
</li>
 </inscope>

 <!-- Items out of scope -->
<outscope>
  <li>mappings between sets or classes;</li>
  <li>relationships that are not classification or set theory relationships; </li>
  <li>entities and relationships specific to continuous sets. </li>
 </outscope>

